{
  "doc_id": "38340",
  "text": "+ CSCs (not on other nonmalignant cells in the pancreas) displayed an up-regulated CD47 which was considered as the \"don't eat me\" signal protecting CSCs from macrophage-mediated phagocytosis [CITATION_1] . Many attempts at finding novel pancreatic CSC inhibitors and agents re-sensitizing CSC to current cytotoxic therapies have been exploited. The ideal therapeutic approaches to CSC elimination include not only killing cancer cells of the primary tumor, but also obtaining a durable clinical response with the prevention of tumor recurrence and metastasis [CITATION_2] . There are several potential targets to inhibit CSCs including pancreatic CSC-specific surface markers [CITATION_3] , stem-cell specific signaling pathways (e.g. Notch, Wnt and Hedgehog [CITATION_4] ), resistance mechanisms, the components of CSC niche [CITATION_5] , and mitochondria dysfunction [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Based on the targets, there are some new drug strategies including salinomycin (Sal), sorafenib [CITATION_8] and metformin [CITATION_9] . It is worth mentioning that Sal, an ionophore antibiotic isolated from Streptomyces albus, selectively targets tumorsphere initiation and the growth of CD133",
